After an hour of user-testing last night, I&#39;d like to withdraw this
proposal (and replace it with another--see next message). There are
two reasons I decided this was a bad idea:

1) Aesthetically, it simply looked bad to use &#39;alternative utter&#39;
followed by &#39;roe&#39;, connected or not. The same can be said for many
other places where this rule would require &#39;alternative uttter&#39;. I
strongly encourage everyone to write a few paragraphs in QS by hand
every day--it has helped me enormously to see how the alphabet works,
and given me a great appreciation of Read&#39;s artistic accomplishment.

2) The cognitive load is increased for the writer. It slowed me down
considerably to have to stop and think about which letter to use.
(Also, thinking ahead to typing with the new keyboard mapping we&#39;ve
discussed, I&#39;d rather not coerce a typist into using &#39;V&#39; so often.)
For the reader there is also a slightly increased cognitive load, in
large part due to the aesthetic issues mentioned above.

So, once again I&#39;m back to the conservative position--the design in
the QM is solid. Let&#39;s use #36 for both /V/ and /@/, and only use
&#39;alternative utter&#39; when it pleases the writer to make an additional
connection.

The only part of this proposal that I&#39;d like to keep is to swap Jon
Zuck&#39;s names &#39;Up&#39; and &#39;Ado&#39;. Any objections?

Ted


