&gt;  &gt; &gt; &gt;out in a very helpful way.
&gt;  &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; That and I live in GMT+1 so I can&#39;t really contribute in your
&gt;  afternoon.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; So as I understand it Utter fills the following roles:
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; 1. The unstressed indefinite vowel. For which we assigned the set
&gt;  &gt; &gt; COMMA to Utter
&gt;  &gt; &gt; 2. The /V/ sound for which we assigned it STRUT
&gt;  &gt; &gt; 3. When combined with Roe, it shares the /3/ sound. That is to
&gt;  say for
&gt;  &gt; &gt; the &quot;ligature&quot; Utter+Roe we assigned the lexical set NURSE
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; 1. COMMA
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Do not use the letter Utter for COMMA. Indeed do not have any letter
&gt;  &gt; &gt; represent the indefinite vowel. Instead write the letter for the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; sound the vowel has when it is stressed in that same root. Write the
&gt;  &gt; &gt; &quot;mental image&quot; of the sound as it were. (sometimes of course this
&gt;  &gt; &gt; turns out to be /V/ in which case one will use Utter after all (see
&gt;  &gt; &gt; below))
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; - This has some whopping great advantages for morphemic writing: many
&gt;  &gt; &gt; roots will no longer vary when suffixes are added:
&gt;  &gt; &gt; e.g.
&gt;  &gt; &gt; with the old approach we had:
&gt;  &gt; &gt; photography, photograph, photographer
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Fee+Owe+Tea+Ox+Gay+Roe...
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Fee+Owe+Tea+UTTER+Gay+Roe...
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Fee+Owe+Tea+Ox+Gay+Roe...
&gt;  &gt; &gt; which very much damages readability compared to TO
&gt;  &gt; &gt; But under the news system this and many other roots will be spelled
&gt;  &gt; &gt; the same no mater the affixes.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -It might actually be easier for writers to do this rather than
&gt;  &gt; &gt; carefully notice the indefinite version of the vowel they are
&gt;  writing.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -When writers make mistakes I think it will mean inserting Utter
&gt;  which
&gt;  &gt; &gt; is the same as the old system anyway.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -It does not fly in the face of the QM too very much
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Having said all that I must say I still have reservations because we
&gt;  &gt; &gt; can not test it out properly. In order to do so would need countless
&gt;  &gt; &gt; users to try to write using this rule and see if in fact it works.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; 2. STRUT
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Utter is still used for STRUT and it becomes its sole role.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; 3. NURSE
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Take NURSE away from the Utter+Roe combination. It is not the sound
&gt;  &gt; &gt; the separate letters make and while it&#39;s close enough for us rhotics,
&gt;  &gt; &gt; it is untenable to ask non-rhotics to use the same symbol (Utter+Roe
&gt;  &gt; &gt; ligature) for /3/ and /Vr/ (e.g. &quot;arrest&quot; vs &quot;nurse&quot;)
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; So this then leaves the question of where to put NURSE instead. I&#39;d
&gt;  &gt; &gt; really strongly discourage adding a truly new letter under all
&gt;  &gt; &gt; circumstances, it is an utterly immense undertaking. So we would
&gt;  &gt; &gt; assign it to an existing letter and I would say that Roe works fine.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Thus: make Roe cover /r/ *and* the lexical set NURSE (which
&gt;  implies /3/ )
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -This trick worked for Ing, Read himself used it there (although we
&gt;  &gt; &gt; expanded it a tad)
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -The problem with the Utter-Roe &quot;ligature&quot; goes away. And if all
&gt;  other
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Roe ligature problems can be accounted for with that &quot;Et/Eight,
&gt;  It/Eat
&gt;  &gt; &gt; , Foot/Ooze neutralization before Roe&quot; law. We have solved it all.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; -&quot;arrest&quot; is spelled Utter-Roe-Et-Sea-Tea. &quot;nurse&quot; is spelled
&gt;  &gt; &gt; No-Roe-Sea. We already had &quot;being&quot; as Bay-Ing and &quot;king&quot; was now
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Key-Ing so it shouldn&#39;t be too shocking.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; My only concern is that this may be trouble for accents that strongly
&gt;  &gt; &gt; roll their Rs; a rolled r is very different than /3/ and could be too
&gt;  &gt; &gt; much to ask of them to use one letter for both. But as a humorous
&gt;  &gt; &gt; aside we will now be able to directly transliterate
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Croatian place names like &quot;Krk&quot;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
